							android:id="@+id/name3"
							android:layout_width="wrap_content"
							android:layout_height="wrap_content"
							android:padding="8dp"
							android:text="Timi Sani"
							android:textSize="12sp"
							android:textColor="#000000"
							android:layout_gravity="left" />
						<TextView
							android:id="@+id/time3"
							android:layout_width="wrap_content"
							android:layout_height="wrap_content"
							android:layout_marginLeft="199dp"
							android:padding="8dp"
							android:text="4 days ago"
							android:textSize="12sp"
							android:textColor="#000000"
							android:singleLine="true"
							android:layout_gravity="right" />
					</LinearLayout>
					<TextView
						android:id="@+id/story3"
						android:layout_width="match_parent"
						android:layout_height="wrap_content"
						android:layout_marginTop="8dp"
						android:layout_marginBottom="8dp"
						android:padding="8dp"
						android:text="Bro, my first day as a bus driver in Lagos was a wild ride, I swear! I was excited, but also nervous, you know\? I had never driven a bus before, and Lagos roads are no joke. But my oga, the conductor, he was chill, he told me &quot;relax, boy, you got this&quot;.\n\nWe set off early, and I was surprised how many people were already waiting at the bus stop. They were all rushing to get in, and I was like &quot;how am I supposed to drive with all these people\?&quot; But my oga just laughed and said &quot;that's Lagos for you, bro&quot;.\n\nAs we hit the road, I realized why they call Lagos the &quot;city that never sleeps&quot;. The traffic was crazy, and drivers were cutting me off left and right. But I held my own, and my oga was guiding me through it all.\n\nWe got to Mushin, and some area boys started begging for money. They were banging on the bus, and I thought &quot;what's going on here\?&quot; But my oga just told me to ignore them, and we kept moving.\n\nWe hit a roadblock at Ojuelegba, and I thought &quot;how are we supposed to get through this\?&quot; But my oga knew the way, and we managed to squeeze through.\n\nWhen we finally reached our destination, I was exhausted, but also hyped. I had made it through my first day as a bus driver in Lagos! The passengers were clapping for me, and my oga was grinning, saying &quot;I told you, boy, you're a natural&quot;.\n\nI learned that day that driving a bus in Lagos takes skill, patience, and a whole lot of courage. But I'm ready for whatever the city throws my way. Bring it on, Lagos!"
						android:textSize="12sp"
						android:textColor="#000000"
						android:lines="6" />
					<LinearLayout
